<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Regrets Greek Trade Blockade of Macedonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702121494 Hamburg DPA in German 1155 GMT 17 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1702121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- On Thursday [17 February], the Federal 
Government expressed regret about the "unilateral" Greek trade 
blockade against Macedonia. The blockade of the access to the 
sea is "noted with concern," Foreign Ministry spokesman Martin 
Erdmann stated on inquiry. Thus, the Federal Government has 
taken up a position against a European Union [EU] partner who is 
also holding the EU Presidency in the first half of 1994. The 
Federal Government wants "more and not less stability" in the 
region. 
  FRG Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel will broach the new 
development within the framework of the EU troika, which had 
previously announced it would meet in Athens this Friday. The 
troika consists of Kinkel and the foreign ministers of Greece 
and Belgium. The three acting EU foreign ministers wanted to 
discuss the Russian attitude toward the Bosnian crisis and the 
NATO ultimatum. Greece's announcement that it will block 
Macedonia's only access to the sea has obviously surprised the 
ministers. 
  Now the extraordinary case might come to pass that Greece 
must expect a contrary decision by the Brussels Commission. The 
Bonn Foreign Ministry pointed out that an EU member "simply 
cannot" block "the trade routes of other EU members" who want to 
conduct trade with the Republic of Macedonia through Salonika. 

</TEXT>

