<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel, Finnish Counterpart Discuss EU Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602191894 Hamburg DPA in German 1658 GMT 16 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1602191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The series of German-Finnish 
consultations on Helsinki's entry into the European Union (EU) 
has continued, with the foreign ministers meeting in Bonn on 
Wednesday [16 Februaqry]. The exchange of opinions between FRG 
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel and his counterpart, Heikki 
Haavisto, focused on Finland's concerns about structural 
adjustments and the special agricultural problems of the Nordic 
winter economy. For Finnish politicians, the negotiations for 
membership have entered the "decisive stage." They are banking 
on German support in Brussels. In January, Foreign Trade 
Minister Perti Salolainen was in Bonn and Parliamentary 
President Ilkka Suominen followed a few days later. 

</TEXT>

