<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Minister Extends Stay of Croatian Refugees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0902203694 Hamburg DPA in German 1813 GMT 9 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0902203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- The interior ministers of the federal and 
laender governments agreed to extend Croatian civil war 
refugees' right to stay in Germany. After a five-hour meeting, 
Interior Minister Manfred Kanther said that due to the difficult 
economic situation in Croatia, and in order to give the state an 
appropriate period of time to look after those returning, the 
repatriation to "pacified regions" in Croatia would be extended. 
  This means that refugees from areas occupied and destroyed 
by 
the Serbs can stay in Germany up to 30 June 1995. The 
repatriation of childless married couples, or single, childless 
adults, will begin on 1 May, and will be finished by 31 October. 
  The interior ministers pointed out, however, that the 
refugees' stay in Germany could only be a temporary one. The 
Federal Government should be asked to discuss the best possible 
solution to the repatriation problem with the Croat Government 
as soon as possible. 

</TEXT>

