<H3> <TI>   Thuringia Heads New Laender in Economic Growth </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702104994 Hamburg DPA in German 0950 GMT 17 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1702104994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Erfurt (DPA) -- With a real economic growth of 11.6 
percent in 1993, Thuringia was right at the head of the new 
laender. The GDP's development was "quite remarkable" compared 
with the average of the new laender, which was 6.3 percent, and 
confirms the economic course that is being followed, Economic 
State Secretary Friedrich Stamm said in Erfurt on Thursday [17 
February]. According to first estimates by the Economic Overall 
Calculation for the Laender Working Group, Saxony came in second 
in 1993 with a real growth of 6.6 percent. 
  East Berlin experienced a growth of 1.8 percent compared 
with 
the previous year, Brandenburg 5.2 percent, Mecklenburg-Western 
Pomerania 5.9 percent, and Saxony-Anhalt 5.6 percent. In 1993, 
however, Thuringia was clearly below the average regarding the 
per capita GDP in the new laender, which, according to Stamm, 
was 13,500 marks. Thuringia reached only 12,500 marks. Stamm 
justified this primarily with the large number of approximately 
70,000 commuters, whose performance is not included in the 
calculations. 

</TEXT>

