<H3> <TI>   Kohl Addresses CDU Rally in Hannover </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602200394 Hamburg DPA in German 1849 GMT 16 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1602200394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hannover (DPA) -- FRG Chancellor Helmut Kohl 
(Christian Democratic Union -- CDU) has again sharply attacked 
Johannes Rau, the Social Democratic Party of Germany's 
presidential candidate. At a CDU election event in Hannover on 
Wednesday evening [16 February], Kohl said Rau had "not felt 
solidarity with the Germans of the GDR" in the second half of 
the 1980's. If the Social Democrats now say that the discussion 
of their behavior toward the former GDR leadership is 
"mudslinging," they only want to divert the people's attention, 
the CDU chairman told 2,500 participants in the event. 
  He sticks to his accusation that at that time leading Social 
Democrats had given in to central demands of ex-GDR head of 
state Erich Honecker. They had advocated dissolving the 
Salzgitter documentation center for human rights violations in 
the GDR and abandoning joint German citizenship. "We never 
betrayed the ideal of German unity, despite all the mistakes we 
made," Kohl cried to the CDU membership. 
  In the event of wage conflicts in the metal industry, Kohl 
warned against strikes and lockouts. He called on both sides of 
industry to solve the wage conflicts at the negotiating table. 
"I do not believe that strikes and lockouts would be helpful 
for jobs and the unemployed in this situation," Kohl said. On 
the contrary, an industrial conflict would "seriously damage" 
the competitiveness of the German economy. Therefore, the 
employers and the trade unions should get together. Kohl again 
presented the latest conclusion of a collective agreement in the 
chemical industry as an "act of reason," both regarding the wage 
agreement of 2 percent and more flexible working hours. 

</TEXT>

