<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Discusses Economy at FDP Rally </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602140094 Hamburg DPA in German 1252 GMT 16 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1602140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bayerbach/Vilshofen (DPA) -- Free Democratic Party 
[FDP] Chairman Klaus Kinkel came out against strikes and 
lockouts in the current difficult economic situation. At his 
party's traditional Ash Wednesday meeting in Bayerbach, Lower 
Bavaria, Kinkel called for a "radical change of thinking" in 
labor market policy. Strikes and lock-outs are "a fist in the 
eye of the economic development"; in view of the high number of 
unemployed, all politicians must work to ensure the recovery of 
the economy. 
  FRG Foreign Minister Kinkel called for a zero round in the 
public sector and a stop to the "galloping state debts," and he 
rejected tax increases for higher earners. The FDP politician 
said that "the old-style social state" is "unsocial, cannot be 
financed, and is counterproductive." It must be placed on a 
narrower but solid basis. The social state must not become a 
"milking cow," Kinkel stressed. 

</TEXT>

