<H3> <TI>   Republikaner Schoenhuber Predicts CSU Decline </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602135994 Hamburg DPA in German 1215 GMT 16 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1602135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Osterhofen (DPA) -- Franz Schoenhuber, chairman of 
the right-wing extremist Republikaner, has predicted that the 
Christian Social Union [CSU] will decline to a 20-percent party. 
"This is the day of change and the greatest day in the history 
of the Republikaner," Schoenhuber stated at his party's Ash 
Wednesday rally in front of an audience of -- according to 
police estimates -- about 6,500 people in a beer tent on the 
outskirts of Osterhofen, Lower Bavaria. The end of the 
traditional parties is near. "I have been chosen by fate to 
help the German people," Schoenhuber said. On Wednesday the 
hour of the CSU's decline tolled in Passau [where the CSU is 
holding its Ash Wednesday rally]. The rise of the Republikaner 
cannot be stopped anymore, Schoenhuber stated. 
  Schoenhuber accused Ignatz Bubis, chairman of the Central 
Council of Jews, of fanning anti-Semitism in the FRG. There is 
no collective guilt for the crimes of the Nazi period. "Today's 
Germany is not guilty. Our only crime in world history was that 
we lost two world wars," Schoenhuber said. 

