<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Investigates Supplies in Somalia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0802111694 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2114 GMT 7 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0802111694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Food Supplies to Army in Somalia </F>
Under Investigation"] 
  [Text] Livorno, 7 Feb (ANSA) -- The Defense Ministry is 
investigating alleged misappropriation and financial wrongdoing 
in contracts for and shipping of food supplies to Italian 
soldiers in Somalia, the former commander of Italian troops with 
the United Nations mission in Somalia, General Bruno Loi, 
revealed Monday [7 February]. "I know that an investigation has 
been under way for some time by Rome army magistrates 
responsible for Somalia," Loi told journalists here, adding: "we 
have total and absolute trust in the magistrature." 
  Loi said he did not know the details of the investigation 
but 
confirmed that Italian troops did receive some shipments of 
spoilt meat, which had to be destroyed "following specific 
bureaucratic procedures." 
  Judicial sources disclosed that magistrates are evaluating 
reports of over-pricing and false bills issued by private 
contractors for food supplies to the military by and the alleged 
sale by Italian soldiers of meat, officially listed as spoilt, 
to soldiers of other countries posted in Somalia. 

</TEXT>

