<H3> <TI>   Prosecution Service Continues To Investigate Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602200694 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
16 Feb 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU1602200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "ban": "Federal Prosecution Service Is </F>
Conducting Investigations of 10 More Serbs"] 
  [Text] Bonn, 15 February -- The Federal Prosecution 
Service is conducting investigations of 10 more Serbs suspected 
of participating in genocide in the war zones of what was 
formerly Yugoslavia. Bonn announced this Tuesday [15 February] 
after an investigating magistrate of the Federal Court applied 
for an arrest warrant for a Serb living in Munich suspected of 
complicity in genocide, murder, and serious assault. This is 
the first time that the "international principle" of the 
criminal code has been employed. Human rights organizations 
have reported for some time that a considerable number of 
"suspected torturers" at Serbian concentration camps were 
residing in Germany. Law enforcement agencies have indications 
of links between Serbian criminal organizations in Germany and 
perpetrators of human rights violations in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

