<H3> <TI>   Economics Ministry Sees Economy Improving </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1602113694 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1028 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1602113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- The German Economics Ministry 
considers the underlying economic trend in Germany as being 
"generally upward," although economic developments varied in 
late 1993 and early 1994. At the same time the high 
unemployment rate remains the key economic problem, according to 
the ministry's economic report for February, published in Bonn 
today. 
  The rebuilding of the east German economy is continuing to 
make "clear progress," the report says. The private sector in 
eastern Germany is "increasingly gaining momentum." [passage 
omitted] 
  The rise in the level of registered unemployed to over 4 
million was "not surprising" and in line with the annual 
forecast. It was due largely to the usual effects of winter on 
the labor market, which would subside during the spring, the 
report predicts optimistically. In addition, the labor market 
is seen as a delayed indicator which "still shows the effects of 
last spring's economic setback in eastern Germany." [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

