<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Revises Optimistic Economic Forecast </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702122394 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU in German 
17 Feb 94 p 11 </F>

<F P=103> AU1702122394 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "ptz": "Rexrodt Admits Setback at the End of </F>
the Year"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- The FRG Economics Ministry's current 
economic forecasting is more restrained than a few weeks ago. 
"Around the end of the year," economic indicators "did not show 
a unified picture; however, the basic trend seems to be upward," 
Rexrodt's ministry now notes. 
  The economists in Bonn are more worried about the situation 
in west German industry. "Orders received and production once 
again declined there during the fourth quarter, following an 
upswing that was observed during the third quarter." All in 
all, adjusted GDP, as a comprehensive expression of the overall 
economic performance, "may have declined a bit" during the last 
quarter of 1993. As a positive element, the ministry notes 
"improved" business expectations in the processing industry. 
  On 21 January, the ministry said: "The slow climb out of the 
deep valley of the recession had already begun in the old 
laender last year. During the second and third quarter, 
GDP...increased slightly and probably stayed at the achieved 
level also during the last quarter of 1993." 

</TEXT>

