<H3> <TI>   Job Cuts in Ruhr Economy Seen Continuing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702122594 Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG in German 17 Feb 94 
p 20 </F>

<F P=103> AU1702122594 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "stw": "Increasing Number of People Losing </F>
Their Jobs in Mines"] 
  [Text] Duisburg -- Although the decline in the Ruhr 
economy -- which is particularly severely affected by the coal 
and steel crises -- seems to have been stopped, more and more 
people in that region are losing their jobs. Surveying 1,700 
companies, the Chambers of Industry and Commerce in Bochum, 
Dortmund, Duisburg, Essen, and Muenster discovered that every 
second firm is thinking of reducing its staff this year. 
  In industry, two out of three companies want to cut jobs. In 
1993, more than 37,000 people in the Rhein and Ruhr areas lost 
their jobs; 13,000 of them had been employed in the mining 
industry. Since a large number of jobs have been destroyed by 
the escalating costs and structural changes, there will be no 
success stories from the labor market in the foreseeable future, 
the president of the Duisburg Chamber of Industry and Commerce, 
Hans Georg Willers, said. 
  In the Ruhr area, 155,000 jobs have been created in the 
service sector over the past 15 years -- yet the same number was 
lost in manufacturing industry. 

</TEXT>

