<F P=100> PORTUGAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Negotiations Seen Only Solution in Angola </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20378B </F>
<F P=103> 94P20378B </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] Writing in the 29 January Lisbon weekly 
SEMANARIO, Jaime Nogueira Pinto accuses unidentified Portuguese 
government officials of ignoring the fact that Jonas Savimbi's 
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) can 
resist "indefinitely" the Angolan Government's attacks, and also 
of believing that the South African elections can significantly 
modify the situation in Angola. Such an attitude, Nogueira Pinto 
contends, "cannot stand up to serious and objective analysis." 
In fact, the responsibility for continued warfare must be 
attributed to the Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola 
(MPLA) and the so-called military bourgeoisie, the hardline 
nucleus of the Armed Forces for the Liberation of Angola 
(FAPLA), which is earning huge commissions on military 
purchases, Nogueira Pinto maintains. In fact, this is the 
faction that rejects a negotiated peace with UNITA--since it 
would mean a loss of power--even as it is loath to lose the 
"respectability" laboriously won in the Washington talks. Hence, 
the continous "provocations" against Savimbi in spite of U.S. 
warnings to Luanda about renewed military escalation. Lisbon's 
interests in Angola will obviously be served by the 
reestablishment of a just and fair peace, to be achieved only 
through compromise and power sharing, Nogueira Pinto concludes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-39520 </DOCNO>
