<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   White House Pressured on Macedonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1602195394 Athens I KATHIMERINI in Greek 16 Feb 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> NC1602195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens I KATHIMERINI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Alexis Papakhelas from Washington] </F>
  [Text] The U.S. State Department leadership is putting 
pressure on the White House to exchange ambassadors with the 
Skopje government soon. The issue is currently being discussed 
by the White House National Security Council and a decision 
could be made by the end of the week. 
  Reliable sources say that Skopjean President Kiro Gligorov 
unofficially assured the State Department that he will make a 
vague statement promising to begin immediate negotiations with 
his government and the parliament to cancel Skopje's flag if the 
United States proceeds in establishing diplomatic relations and 
Greece agrees to continue dialogue under the auspices of Cyrus 
Vance. 
  The State Department believes that diplomatic relations 
should be established by 1 March, arguing that the political 
cost for Greece would be less if this happened now rather than 
later. At the same time, the Americans do not want the exchange 
of ambassadors to coincide with the Greek prime minister's visit 
to the United States, which is scheduled for 22 April. 
  U.S. diplomats are also arguing that the crisis in Bosnia 
and 
the possibility of air raids makes it necessary to handle 
immediately any pending issues in U.S.-Skopjean relations. The 
United States has noted the nationalistic upsurge that has been 
going on in Greece during the last few days but believes that it 
will not turn into tangible, harsh measures against Skopje in 
the economic relations sector. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

