<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Kozyrev, European Ministers on Bosnia, Macedonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1702183794 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 1600 
GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1702183794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Foivos Karzis] </F>
  [Text] Belgian Foreign Minister Willy Claes and Hans van 
den Broek, European Community commissioner on foreign affairs, 
appeared extremely reserved about the measures the Greek 
Government has taken on Skopje. Claes and van den Broek arrived 
in Athens a short time ago together with German Foreign Minister 
Klaus Kinkel and his Russian counterpart Andrey Kozyrev to 
attend tomorrow's meeting between the European troika and Russia. 
  Claes said he does not hide his concern and will continue to 
insist that the Athens-Skopje dialogue resume at the United 
Nations, something, as he put it, that everybody in Europe 
considers as the best way to safeguard the good neighborliness 
between the two countries and, primarily, something that ensures 
the smooth functioning of the European Union as a whole and 
toward its neighbors. 
  Van den Broek said he will seek clarification on the 
measures 
from the Greek Government and will also examine their 
compatibility with the legal framework of the European Union. 
  Their disagreement over the Bosnian issue is clear. Kozyrev 
expressed his clear opposition to the NATO threat of bombings 
and implied that any bombing would also affect Russia's 
participation in the NATO Partnership for Peace plan concerning 
the accession of Eastern countries. Kozyrev left open the 
possibility of Russian blue helmet [United Nations] troops going 
to Sarajevo to safeguard peace as early as the weekend. 
  Claes and van den Broek expressed their optimism that 
bombings will be averted but also stated the conviction that the 
strict NATO ultimatum was decoded correctly and both Europe and 
the Atlantic Alliance should insist on it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

