<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   German Leaders React to Russian Role in Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kinkel: No Peace Without Russia </H4>
<F P=102> AU1802113694 Hamburg DPA in German 0947 GMT 18 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1802113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Athens -- According to Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel, peace in Bosnia will not be possible without Russia. 
This was pointed out by Kinkel in Athens this morning after 
talks with his Russian counterpart Andrey Kozyrev. The letter 
by Russian President Boris Yeltsin to the leader of the Bosnian 
Serbs, Radovan Karadzic, has created favorable preconditions for 
a settlement in Bosnia, he stated. 
  However, Kinkel warned against too much enthusiasm. "The 
NATO ultimatum will continue to be valid. It apparently had the 
desired effect." To achieve a peaceful settlement in Bosnia, 
Russia must by all means be involved in the talks. Kozyrev 
stated in Athens that the promise by the Bosnian Serbs to 
withdraw their weapons in exchange for the deployment of 400-500 
Russian blue berets in and around Sarajevo is the "beginning of 
the end of the war in Bosnia." 
  A new round of political dialogue between Russia and the 
European Union started in Athens this morning. It is being 
attended by the executive foreign ministers of the European 
Union from Belgium, Greece -- which currently holds the 
chairmanship of the European Union -- and its successor Germany. 
  Referring to Greece's unilateral action against the former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- it closed the port of Salonika 
for all deliveries to and from Skopje -- Kinkel stressed that 
this was an "unusual step that does not correspond to practices 
within the community." Exerting pressure is no instrument for 
settling such issues. "We do not need a destabilization of 
Macedonia," he pointed out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

