<H3> <TI>   European Commission `Furious' at Greek Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1702154294 The Hague ANP in Dutch 1122 GMT 17 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1702154294 </F>
<F P=104>  The Hague ANP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed KVB: "European Commission Reacts Strongly to </F>
Greek Embargo Against Macedonia"; as released by The Hague ANP 
Database] 
  [Excerpt] Brussels, 17 Feb (ANP) -- The European Commission 
is furious about the Greek embargo against Macedonia. 
Commission President Delors will make a declaration on Thursday 
afternoon [17 February] saying in so many words that the move is 
not in the spirit of the Union treaty. 
  Diplomats say that the unilateral move by Athens is not 
conducive to the European Union's [EU] "cohesion." Greece 
currently holds the EU presidency. "The Union must stick 
together as a union," a spokesman said. "The Greek move does 
not contribute to this." 
  Resentful reactions to Athens' move had already been seen at 
political talks between top civil servants from the member 
states on Tuesday evening. It is usual for a member state 
taking measures outside the Union to first contact the council. 
However, the Greek representative appeared to be clearly 
embarrassed by his government. The argument that a Greek harbor 
was concerned did not sound very convincing to those present, 
according to a diplomat. 
  The question will probably come up in the sidelines of the 
talks to be held in Athens on Thursday and Friday by the 
ministerial EU troika. This troika consists of Greece, Belgium 
and Germany, the present, past, and future EU presidents. A 
spokesman said it was not usual for the troika to publicly put a 
member state in the pillory without prior consultation with the 
Union member states. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

