<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev, Kinkel Issue Joint Appeal on Russian Reform </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702193394 Hamburg DPA in German 1832 17 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1702193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- In a joint appeal, Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev and his German counterpart Klaus Kinkel 
have described strengthening Russia's reform policy as the most 
effective defense against nationalism. Kozyrev, who has often 
made contradictory statements and rejected NATO influence in the 
East as well as a tough military stance against the Serbs in 
recent weeks, had the joint appeal with Kinkel published in the 
FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE (Friday [18 February] edition). 
  In the article, the foreign ministers, who are meeting in 
Athens on Thursday and Friday, conjure up a "long-term strategic 
vision." The Partnership for Peace offered by NATO is not 
mentioned, but what is mentioned is a strategy for partnership 
that must entail support for political and economic reforms in 
Russia and neighboring countries. According to the paper, the 
Foreign Ministry stressed that in view of the outcome of the 
Russian elections, Kozyrev accorded particular importance to 
continuing free market economic development in drawing up the 
appeal. 

</TEXT>

