<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Welcomes Lower Discount Rate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702144494 Hamburg DPA in German 1342 GMT 17 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1702144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- Finance Minister Theo Waigel welcomed the 
lowering of the discount rate. "With this, the Bundesbank 
continues its course of gradually lowering the interest rate 
level in Germany," he said in Bonn. The Bundesbank decision and 
the government's consistent austerity and consolidation policy 
strengthen the conditions for an inflation-free upward economic 
trend. The interest rate reduction is also a call upon the wage 
round partners to create favorable conditions for an economic 
recovery by concluding agreements that provide stability, Waigel 
said. 
  The German Banking Association spoke of a "decision 
appropriate in the current situation." With this, the 
Bundesbank continues a successful policy of reducing interest 
rates step by step, without creating any confusion in the 
capital market or the international financial markets. Like the 
Bundesbank, the Banking Association also expects a steadying of 
prices in the course of 1994. The Banking Association once 
again called on the wage round partners and the financial 
policymakers of the federal and laender governments to meet 
their responsibilities concerning stability. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

