<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Napolitano Comments on U.S. Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1102131094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2047 GMT 10 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1102131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Elections: `U.S. Impartial,' </F>
Napolitano Says"] 
  [Text] Washington, 10 Feb (ANSA) -- United States officials 
are impartial with regard to Italy's coming general elections, 
according to visiting Italian House Speaker Giorgio Napolitano 
in Washington Thursday [10 February]. 
  Over a two-day period, Wednesday and Thursday, Napolitano 
has 
met with his U.S. counterpart Thomas Foley; with the chairman of 
the house foreign affairs committee, Lee Hamilton; with former 
national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinsky; with the State 
Department's director for European Affairs, Stephen Oxman and 
with the head of the International Monetary Fund, Michael 
Camdessus. 
  Napolitano said he received the distinct impression that 
while American authorities took a keen interest in Italian 
affairs, they were determined to remain impartial with regard to 
the various political forces in play in Italy today. Americans 
are seeking to get a better handle on the envisioned government 
prospects of the Democratic Party of the Left (the former 
Communist Party), the evolution of the MSI [Italian Social 
Movement] neofascist party as led by Gianfranco Fini, and the 
entrance onto the political scene of media mogul Silvio 
Berlusconi, who they are quick to liken to Ross Perot, he said. 
  With regard to the Left Democrats, Napolitano stressed that 
they were interested in pursuing the policy of recovery and 
reconstruction launched by the present Ciampi government. 
  However, Napolitano would not be drawn into making any 
guesses as to the outcome of the March general elections, 
insisting that the results were unpredictable, although he was 
fairly certain that the toughest and most innovative of the 
Ciampi government's policies would be continued. Italians are 
demanding renewal and recovery, he added. 

</TEXT>

