<H3> <TI>   Scalfaro, Berlusconi Hold `Very Cordial' Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1602123594 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1721 GMT 15 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1602123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Scalfaro Meets Berlusconi"] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 15 Feb (ANSA) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi 
Scalfaro met here this morning with TV tycoon Silvio Berlusconi 
in his function as leader of the Forza Italia (Go Italy) 
political movement for talks that Berlusconi described later as 
"very cordial." 
  He said that, in the 75-minute conversation, he had 
primarily 
described how the new moderately conservative political grouping 
had been created and what had been done to draw lists of 
candidates with a good chance of beating the progressives. 
  Berlusconi also admitted that he had talked to Scalfaro 
about 
his brother Paolo's judicial problems thanks to allegations that 
he paid kickbacks to sell real estate. "I informed him of my 
assessment of the fact and the situation," said Berlusconi. 
  Berlusconi also said that moderate conservatives such as the 
ex-Christian Democrats of the People's Party and Pact for Italy 
would create "uncertainty" in the voters by claiming to stand 
for the bloc of moderate opinion known as the Centre in the old 
political system. 
  "They are putting themselves in a position that is difficult 
to explain to the people," he said adding that they face defeat 
unless they say which side they are on. He also defended his 
electoral alliance with the Northern League and the extreme 
rightists of the Italian Social Movement. 
  In other remarks, Berlusconi maintained his potential 
candidacy as prime minister. 

</TEXT>

