<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows High Percentage of Undecided Voters </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1402130994 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1506 GMT 11 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1402130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Two Out of Three Italians Undecided, </F>
Directa Poll"] 
  [Text] Rome, 11 Feb (ANSA) -- Two out of three Italians 
have not yet decided what party they will vote for in the March 
27 elections, according to a Directa poll of 1,210 telephone 
interviews in 92 municipalities nationwide. 
  The poll results, released Friday [11 February], showed that 
67.6 percent of those interviewed replied "no" when asked if 
they had decided which party they will support, while only 32.4 
percent said they had. The highest percentage of undecided was 
among women between the ages of 35 and 54, fluctuating between 
73 and 75 percent in different municipalities. 
  "The results show a high level of confusion among Italian 
voters and allow us to affirm undeniably that the percentages of 
support attributed to various parties or alliances are totally 
unreliable because, by referring to only one third of the 
electorate, they are scientifically unfounded," Directa stated, 
referring to polls that claimed Go Italy [Forza Italia], led by 
entrepreneur Paolo Berlusconi, topped the ratings with 24 
percent. 
  The number of undecided voters, Directa said, was the 
highest 
reported in the last 15 years just six weeks away from elections. 

</TEXT>

