<F P=101> Denmark </F>
<H3> <TI>   Helveg Petersen Rejects Russian Peacekeeping Call </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1702125094 Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE in Danish 16 Feb 
94 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1702125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Copenhagen BERLINGSKE TIDENDE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Danish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Bo Jeppesen report: "Danish `No' to Peace Role"] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Niels Helveg Petersen (Radical 
Liberal Party) yesterday rejected the proposal that Denmark 
should assume a leading role in peacekeeping operations in the 
former Soviet Union. 
  BERLINGSKE TIDENDE was able to report on Monday [14 
February] 
that the Coordinating Council for Military Affairs in the CIS 
(the former Soviet Union) has asked Denmark to assume this 
leadership role. 
  "It is probably wrong to envisage that Denmark or any other 
country should play a special role. The United Nations or the 
CSCE should play such a role; we have to say that it is 
international organizations that should play a special role in 
the resolution of conflicts between Russia and its new 
neighbors," Helveg Petersen told the TV-Avisen program last 
night. 
  But he is positive to the idea that Denmark should make 
troops available. 
  "Denmark has peacekeeping operations experience that is 
unique. We have been involved in many such operations, and we 
have trained personnel in the Danish defense forces and 
elsewhere to take on such operations. So if the United Nations 
and the CSCE become involved in these operations in the former 
Soviet Union, well, naturally Denmark must also give 
consideration to the role it should play." 

</TEXT>

