<H3> <TI>   Trade Minister Denies EU Membership `Secret' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1602130294 Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 15 Feb 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM1602130294 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Gloomy Future If We Vote `No'"] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Trade Minister Pertti Salolainen (National 
Coalition Party) has rejected claims that the report on the 
effects of Finland's staying outside the EU [European Union] has 
been classified as secret. 
  "The opposite is the case. The results of the investigation 
must be made public as quickly as possible," he said yesterday 
when commenting on reports in ILTA SANOMAT that the government 
is trying to keep the "report on the repercussions" secret. 
  The report says that a section of industry would move 
abroad, 
as would many jobs. Nor would there be new investment in a 
Finland that had placed itself outside the European Union. 
  According to Salolainen, the reason why the government has 
not made the report public is that the work on it is still 
continuing. For example, the sections on agriculture, regional 
policy, and foreign policy are still only half finished. 
  The report, sections of which have now leaked out to the 
general public, is the report that the government commissioned 
in spring 1993 and that is to figure in the EU debate prior to 
the referendum later this year. 

</TEXT>

