<H3> <TI>   Greek Agriculture Minister Holds Talks in Helsinki </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1602141694 Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 15 Feb 94 
p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PM1602141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [FINSKA NOTISBYRAN report: "Cautious Greek Minister in </F>
Helsinki"] 
  [Text] Greece's agriculture minister thinks that the EU's 
[European Union] current agricultural system was not designed to 
take account of the sort of conditions that prevail in Finland. 
Agriculture Minister Yeoryios Moraitis said in Helsinki 
yesterday that in the membership negotiations there are still 
open questions of this type that need bold political decisions. 
  Greece currently holds the EU presidency, and Moraitis will 
therefore play a central role when the EU reaches a decision on 
its agricultural goals in the membership negotiations. 
  Yesterday Moraitis held five hours of talks with Agriculture 
and Forestry Minister Martti Pura, and he also met Foreign 
Minister Heikki Haavisto and Foreign Trade Minister Pertti 
Salolainen. 
  After the meeting Pura said that there had been no 
negotiations, but that Moraitis had been briefed on Finland's 
goals. No new issues emerged in the negotiations, Pura said. 
  Moraitis was tight-lipped when it came to answering 
questions 
-- for example, about Spain's proposal that the new member 
countries' net contributions should be targeted in support to 
the poorest member countries. As the holder of the presidency, 
Greece must be cautious and not comment on something that will 
perhaps not happen, Moraitis said. 

</TEXT>

