<H3> <TI>   Estimates Show Profit From EU Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1602125694 Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET in Swedish 15 Feb 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM1602125694 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HUFVUDSTADSBLADET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Brussels Estimates: Finland Will </F>
Make a Profit in the EU"] 
  [Text] Unlike Sweden, Finland will be a net recipient in 
the event of EU [European Union] membership. This is shown by 
the latest estimates from the EU Commission. 
  This means that Finland will receive more from the EU budget 
than it pays in. 
  According to the Commission's estimates, Finland's net 
contribution will amount to around ECU100 million, corresponding 
to something over 600 million markkas. 
  This is due to the seriously weakened Finnish economy and 
the 
large payments that are expected to be paid back to Finland for 
agriculture and regional policy support. 
  But a spokesman for the Commission stressed that this figure 
should be taken with a pinch of salt. As long as membership 
negotiations have not settled the chapters on agriculture and 
regional support, the calculations are unreliable. 
  The other three countries -- Sweden, Austria, and Norway -- 
will be net contributors in the event of membership -- that is, 
they will pay more into the EU budget than they will receive in 
return in payments from the EU's various funds. And Sweden will 
be the biggest net contributor, with probably the highest 
membership fee per inhabitant. 

</TEXT>

