<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Spokesman on Measures Against Macedonia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1702134094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1702134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou clarified that 
our country is ready for talks with Skopje, but remains firm on 
the issue of the state's name. [passage omitted] 
  Asked whether Greece violates international law with the 
measures against Skopje, government spokesman Evangelos 
Venizelos said the Greek Government calmly and carefully 
examined all aspects, both legal and political. On the goods 
that are allowed to move from Thessaloniki port to and from 
Skopje, Venizelos said the National Economy Ministry will issue 
a circular with instructions based on the decisions made by the 
government yesterday. The ministry will define the scope of the 
customs authorities' authority. He said, however, that there is 
a complete ban excluding only diplomatic, UN, and CSCE 
delegations. [passage omitted] 
  Diplomatic correspondent Mirella Kalostipi reported a short 
time ago that with the adoption of measures against Skopje, the 
Greek Government aims to make this state realize its provocative 
stance toward Greece. According to reliable information, the 
measures may become even harsher if Skopje continues its 
intransigence. The Greek side is convinced that the specific 
measures do not violate either European or international law. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou today said that 
Skopje should finally get reasonable. Asked whether the 
measures were adopted at the wrong time, Papandreou said the 
time was wrong for various countries to recognize Skopje. 
Mentioning that there is a crisis in Athens-Skopje relations, 
Papandreou said he hopes a solution is found through this 
crisis. He added that the Greek Government believes the 
measures will lead more directly and effectively to a solution 
of the problem. [passage omitted] 
  Asked how much the measures against Skopje will affect the 
crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina and the possible bombing, the 
government spokesman said the issue of Bosnia-Herzegovina and 
NATO decisions have no connection with Skopje. 

</TEXT>

