<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Leader, Spokesman View Macedonian Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1702190594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1600 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1702190594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Official opposition leader Miltiadhis Evert met 
Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou at 1400 today in the Maximos 
Palace. Afterward, Evert told correspondents that he and the 
prime minister discussed the sphere of our national issues, 
which are intense these days. Evert said he could not detail 
the discussion. He said: I will say only that New Democracy, as 
a national party, will keep the national front firm. The 
official opposition leader noted that he was not satisfied with 
all the answers and thoughts raised in his talks with the prime 
minister. 
  Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos stressed: The Greek 
Government will not brief foreign governments on its decision 
[concerning relations with Skopje], which was made within the 
framework of national sovereignty and with great wisdom. But 
the spokesman did say that Foreign Ministry Secretary General 
Ambassador Khristos Zakharakis will brief the permanent members 
of the UN Security Council. Venizelos made it clear that 
humanitarian aid is excluded from the trade blockade of Skopje. 
The blockade includes shipments that are in transit through 
Greece unless such transport involves items from diplomatic, 
United Nations, and CSCE missions on the territory of the former 
Yugoslavia. [passage omitted] 
  Greece warns that stronger measures will be implemented 
unless Skopje's intransigence is bent. Greece is also preparing 
to refute--on a political and legal level--the objections by the 
European partners and the United States. The main axis of the 
Greek argument will be that Greece follows international law. 
Reference will also be made to the articles of the European 
Unification Treaty that give member countries the right to 
invoke action for reasons of particular national interest. 
  Reportedly, there is already a report at the prime 
minister's 
office and at Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias' office. It 
was prepared by the legal department of the Foreign Ministry and 
includes the arguments the Greek representatives will put 
forward abroad and with international organizations. 

</TEXT>

