<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Belgium's Claes Comments on Yeltsin, NATO Demand </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1802122394 Brussels BELGA in French 2358 GMT 17 Feb 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1802122394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed SDC/JLV: "Yeltsin Puts Pressure on UN </F>
Security Council Members"; as released by Brussels BELGA 
Database] 
  [Text] Athens, 18 Feb (BELGA) -- Belgian Foreign Minister 
Willy Claes confirmed on Thursday evening [17 February] in 
Athens that the Russian President Boris Yeltsin had sent a 
letter to those countries in the UN Security Council with troops 
in Bosnia. In the letter, he stated that the "ultimatum set by 
NATO is illegal" and "that a new resolution must be adopted in 
the UN Security Council." 
  If Russia did not obtain a satisfactory response on this 
point, then "we cannot be held responsible for the possible 
consequences arising from NATO air strikes against the Bosnian 
Serbs," the Russian president continued. 
  Yeltsin sent this letter to the French, British and Spanish 
Governments. 
  Claes said Yeltsin regretted "not having been sufficiently 
informed of the actions concerning Bosnia, and recalls that the 
ultimatum set by NATO is not covered by resolutions voted by the 
UN Security Council." 
  The Russian foreign minister had declared, however, that 
"air 
strikes could be justified as a final resort." 
  Russian opposition to air strikes is certainly not new, but 
it is the first time the Russian president, who generally is 
moderate in his relations with the West, has adopted such a 
stiff tone. 
  In reaction to Yeltsin's letter, Claes recalled that the 
existing resolutions (836 and 844) "do constitute an adequate 
legal basis for air strikes." "Therefore a new UN Security 
Council resolution is not necessary," the Belgian minister added. 
  "It makes no sense to claim that we want to minimalize 
Russia's role in the Bosnia question. On the contrary, the 
Europe Union [EU] wants Russia and the United States to play a 
more active role in seeking peace in Bosnia," Claes added. 
  Finally the Belgian minister said he was "optimistic" about 
a 
peaceful conclusion to the Sarajevo crisis after the Russian 
announcement of an agreement on the withdrawal of Bosnian Serb 
heavy weapons. 
  On Friday Claes will participate with his Greek and German 
colleagues in a meeting of the European "troika" -- the 
outgoing, current and future EU presidencies -- with the Russian 
Foreign Minister A. Kozyrev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

