<H3> <TI>   German Leaders React to Russian Role in Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kohl Telephones Yeltsin </H4>
<F P=102> AU1802120294 Hamburg DPA in German 1050 GMT 18 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1802120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- On Friday [18 February], Federal 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl had another telephone conversation with 
Russian President Yeltsin to discuss recent developments 
regarding the withdrawal of all heavy arms from the city of 
Sarajevo, which is being besieged by the Serbs. Government 
Spokesman Dieter Vogel said in Bonn that the main point of the 
conversation was to urge the Serbs to withdraw their heavy arms 
or put them under UN control still before the ultimatum expires 
on Monday. 
  Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, of the Free Democratic Party 
of Germany, is also involved in Kohl's talks with the Russian 
leadership. According to Vogel, the Federal Government paid 
tribute to Russia's efforts to ease tensions in Sarajevo. The 
Serbian side is now expected to finally raise the siege of the 
Bosnian capital. 

</TEXT>

