<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Czech Defense Minister Explains Plan for Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2002200294 Prague CTK in English 1922 GMT 20 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2002200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Feb 20 (CTK) -- Czech Defence Minister 
Antonin Baudys today said his peace initiative on Bosnia was 
based on a non-military principle and did not reckon on the use 
of foreign armies there. 
  Talking to journalists aboard a plane en route to Turkey, he 
said that an analysis of the situation in Bosnia had shown that 
the possibility of a peaceful settlement in the area was almost 
equal to zero. 
  In Bosnia, each of the three warring parties to the 
conflict, 
the Catholic Croats, the Orthodox Serbs and the Muslims, has its 
supporters abroad to whom it trusts, Baudys said and added that 
his initiative ensued from this very prerequisite. 
  Baudys's initiative, presented at a press conference in 
Prague yesterday, envisages the creation of a UN executive 
goodwill committee which would oversee the peace process in 
Bosnia and in which selected countries, such as Russia, Greece, 
Pakistan, Turkey, France and Italy, would participate. 
  According to Baudys, Bosnia would be administered by a 
police 
force and an unbiased UN committee with powers freely obtained 
from the three hostile parties for a definite period of time. 
  Baudys said he was open to any discussion concerning more 
detailed information or variants to his proposal providing the 
world community showed interest in it. 
  He confirmed he had not consulted the initiative with 
government or parliament but only with a group of his friends. 
He, however, did not elaborate whether the group included some 
government members, for instance Foreign Minister Josef 
Zieleniec. 
  Baudys said he expected to get first foreign response in 
Ankara. 

</TEXT>

