<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkey Rejects Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2102151394 Prague CTK in English 1120 GMT 21 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2102151394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara Feb 21 (CTK) -- Turkish Defence Minister 
Mehmet Golhan today practically rejected a personal initiative 
on a solution to the situation in Bosnia put forward by Antonin 
Baudys, his Czech counterpart. 
  At his meeting with Baudys, who is currently on a three-day 
visit to Ankara, Golhan said that the initiative "does not 
reflect the current situation in Bosnia and Herzegovina." The 
Turkish side above all rejects the assumption that the conflict 
was religiously motivated. 
  "In our opinion, it is above all necessary to keep intact 
the 
territorial integrity of the Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina, 
a state recognised by the United Nations and the international 
community," Golhan said, adding that "Bosnia and Herzegovina 
must not be partitioned." 
  He hinted that Ankara's view is that the Bosnian (mainly 
Muslim) Government led by President Alija Izetbegovich is the 
only legal party to the conflict. 
  Handing over powers to an executive goodwill committee is 
seen as inadequate because it basically involves the division of 
the republic, Golhan said. 
  At the same time, however, Golhan praised Baudys's 
initiative, saying that "similar proposals contribute to ending 
the war in Bosnia and that is what makes them welcome." 

</TEXT>

