<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel: Sarajevo Success `A Beginning' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2102090394 Hamburg DPA in German 0722 GMT 21 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2102090394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DPA) -- On Monday [21 February], FRG Foreign 
Minister Klaus Kinkel stated with satisfaction that the 
objectives of the NATO ultimatum on Sarajevo have been reached. 
Virtually all heavy weapons of the Bosnian Serbs have been 
removed from the 20-km zone or placed under UN supervision, he 
said on Deutschlandradio. Since this is only a small step on the 
road ahead, political talks must begin immediately, Kinkel said. 
It cannot be right that the weapons that have been withdrawn 
appear in other combat zones, for example, Tuzla and Bihac. 
  Kinkel evaluated the solution achieved in and around 
Sarajevo 
as a beginning that will "hopefully" be translated into an 
"overall solution," because there are "many Sarajevos." The 
cease-fire has to be consolidated and the siege of the Bosnian 
capital has to be called off. 
  There is no reason for euphoria, the minister said. The main 
work is starting now. Here the Germans could offer their 
"mediating good offices." Croats and Muslims also have to be 
brought together, in order to achieve a political solution. 
Kinkel said that Russia's role is important. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

