OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2102190494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The Free Democratic Party of Germany 
[FDP] does not want to commit itself to a date for deciding on a 
statement concerning a potential coalition after the 16 October 
Bundestag elections. After the FDP Presidium's weekly meeting 
on Monday [21 February], FDP Chairman Klaus Kinkel only said 
that the FDP will announce "where we will go" at an "appropriate 
time" before the elections. 
  He left it open whether this is to be done at the federal 
party congress in September. The Presidium decided on Monday to 
move the date of the congress, which was originally planned for 
17-18 September in Berlin, to 3-4 September in Nuremberg in 
order to gain more time before the Bundestag elections. The 
liberals want to make an election appeal in Nuremberg. The 
election program is to be adopted at a preceding federal party 
congress in Rostock on 3-5 June. 

