<F P=101> Switzerland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federal Council Report on Foreign Policy Approved </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1002151894 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1049 GMT 9 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1002151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed BB: "Swiss Foreign Policy Report: No </F>
Unanimous Approval From Committee"; as released by Bern 
ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Bern, 9 Feb (ATS) -- The National Council's Foreign 
Policy Committee, chaired by Ernst Muehlemann [Radical 
Democratic Party, Canton of Thurgau], approved the Federal 
Council's report on Swiss foreign policy and the report on 
neutrality. However, approval was not unanimous: 17 votes to 
five. A minority requested that the report be sent back to the 
Federal Council with the article asking for European Union [EU] 
membership removed. 
  According to a press release issued on Wednesday [9 
February], the majority approved the government's global 
strategy. For domestic political reasons, however, a minority 
wanted the Federal Council to consider EU membership not as a 
goal, but as a possible solution depending on circumstances. 
  Similarly, during the discussion on neutrality it was stated 
that this traditional rule must not be considered an end in 
itself but rather a means of defending the nation's interests. 
This maxim cannot remain inflexible if external circumstances 
change. 
  As an initial success of the bilateral Swiss-EC 
negotiations, 
the committee cited the rapidly reached agreement on the rules 
of origin. The issue of what strategy to adopt in these 
negotiations was also raised. The committee expressed its 
support for the new coordinator, Secretary of State Jakob 
Kellenberger. 
<H5>  Concern Over Events in Bosnia </H5>
  In light of the situation in Bosnia, the committee expressed 
its concern at the violent attacks on the civilian population. 
The committee condemned the massacre of 5 February in Sarajevo 
and the blatant and continued violation of the Geneva 
Convention. It demanded in the strongest terms that, despite 
attempts at "ethnic cleansing," a multicultural society be 
guaranteed in Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

