<F P=101> Switzerland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Koller, Hungarian Minister Sign Repatriation Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR0802110694 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1355 GMT 4 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR0802110694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed BB: "Agreement Signed With Hungary on </F>
Repatriation -- Arnold Koller Receives Imre Konya"; as released 
by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Bern, 4 Feb (ATS) -- On Friday [4 February], Federal 
Councillor Arnold Koller received Imre Konya, the new Hungarian 
minister of interior, in Bern. According to a communique issued 
by the Justice and Police Department, the meeting dealt 
primarily with the political issues of migration and domestic 
security. In addition, the ministers signed an agreement which 
settles the reciprocal acceptance of illegal immigrants staying 
in either country. 
  This bilateral agreement also lays down the transportation 
conditions for those illegal foreigners from other countries 
being repatriated by Switzerland or Hungary. This measure is 
important for the repatriation of rejected asylum-seekers. 
  The agreement is based on the principles embodied in the 
agreements signed by Hungary with neighboring countries. The 
decisive factor for repatriation is not the illegal crossing of 
the border, but the fact that the person was previously a legal 
and long-term resident of another country. 
  Imre Konya also expressed his wish to see increased 
collaboration in the fight against terrorism and organized 
crime. According to the communique, both ministers agree that 
an effective migration policy and an efficient fight against 
organized crime must come through close international 
cooperation. 

</TEXT>

