<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministers Meet at Aviano To Discuss Bosnia </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sarajevo Ultimatum Remains in Force </H4>
<F P=102> AU2102124894 Paris AFP in English 1245 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2102124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Naples, Italy, Feb 21 (AFP) -- The NATO ultimatum to 
withdraw all heavy weapons from a 20 kilometre (12.5 mile) 
exclusion zone around Sarajevo is still in force and weapons 
found within the zone will be subject to air strikes, the NATO 
commander for southern Europe said Monday [21 February]. 
  "Our mission is not over," Admiral Jeremy Boorda said. "Any 
weapons found that are not under control will be subject to air 
strike. Any shelling of Sarajevo will be cause for a strike 
recommendation against the party doing the shelling," he also 
said. 
  Meanwhile verification by UN forces on the ground and NATO 
reconnaissance aircraft continued Monday, the admiral said. 
  The North Atlantic Treaty Organisation said all heavy 
weapons 
had to be withdrawn 20 kilometres (12.5 mile) from the center of 
Sarajevo or placed under UN control. 

</TEXT>

