<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman: Action `Violates Trade Laws' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2102162094 Paris AFP in English 1610 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2102162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Feb 21 (AFP) -- The European Commission 
believes that Greece's economic blockade of Macedonia [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] violates European 
laws on free trade with a third state, a spokesman for the 
Commission said here Monday [21 February]. 
  "Greece's decisions clearly violate the trade laws" of the 
European Community, he said, adding that the EC Commission is 
waiting for Greece to justify its action as called for by the 
law. 
  According to EC law, any country that imposes such sanctions 
must prove that it was forced to undertake such a move because 
its security was threatened. 
  In the northwestern Greek town of Ioannina on Monday, Greek 
Foreign Minister Carolos Papoulias issued a message to his EC 
partners saying that "it is not Greece that has hurt the EC's 
solidarity but rather those who have supported (FYROM's) 
intransigence." 
  Greece, which holds the rotating presidency of the EC, said 
it had been forced to impose the punitive blockade last week 
after the United States "erroneously" recognised FYROM before 
the latter had responded positively to Greece's demands for 
Skopje to work towards stability in the region. 
  Most of Athens' EC partners have also recognized FYROM. 
  Greece accuses FYROM of usurping a name which Athens says is 
solely part of Greek heritage and of harbouring expansionist 
ambitions over the Greek province of the same name. 
  "We are not asking anything from anyone, the only thing we 
want is respect for our borders, respect for the rights of the 
Greek minority (in FYROM) and respect for our history," 
Papoulias said. 
  Along the Greek-FYROM border Monday, convoys of trucks could 
be seen waiting for Greek border guards to check their 
merchandise before being allowed to proceed. 
  The Greek blockade covers oil and other essential supplies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

