<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Increased Number of Foreigners Turned Back at Border </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2002203894 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 19-20 Feb 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> AU2002203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [APA report: "More Foreigners Turned Back at the Border"] </F>
  [Text] Vienna -- Austria's borders last year were largely 
closed: The number of people who were turned back, expelled, or 
deported from Austria increased greatly in 1993. According to 
the Interior Ministry, this is proof of the effectiveness of 
pollice measures regarding aliens. 
  A total of 160,394 people were turned back at the border, 
approximately 49,000 more than in 1992. The number of 
expulsions rose from 1,723 to 3,846. The number of deportations 
-- 8,857 (plus 1,501) -- almost reached the level of 1991. 
  Only the number of people who were sent back to the country 
where they were previously fell from 8,221 to 5,437. This 
refers to people who enter the country illegally and are sent 
back to the country where they were previously within 14 days. 
  The reason the number decreased by so much is mainly because 
the number of illegal border crossings recently has been 
steadily declining. Romanians, in particular, who used to 
attempt to cross the border illegally in relatively large 
numbers are not entering the country illegally as often anymore. 
The reason for this is relatively simple: Hungarian checks are 
much stricter now, and the route through the former Yugoslavia 
is largely blocked by the war in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

